<leme no="747">

<section type="Title-page">
<page sig="[A0r]">
<f type="r">The Compleat English
Schoolmaster.
OR THE
Most Natural and Easie Method
Of Spelling English.
ACCORDING
To the present proper pronuntia&shy;
tion of the Language in <f type="i">OXFORD</f> and 
<f type="i">LONDON.</f>
WHEREIN
Children and Foreigners shall have the whole Body
of English words in the plainest order digested
and divided to their hands.

To which is added

<f type="i">An Appendix of useful Observations
on Orthography.</f>

<term lang="la"><f type="i">Est etiam sua Loquentibus Observatio, sua scribentibus. Quint. Iust. I.</f> I.c.6
<f type="i">Consuetudinem sermonie, vocabo consensum Eruditorum; sicut vivendi
consensum Bonorum, id. ib.</f>
<f type="i">Verum Orthographia quoque consuetudini servit, ideoque s&aelig;pe mutata
est. l.</f> I.c.7.</term>

<f type="i">LONDON</.i>,

Printed for <f type="i">Peter Parker</f>, at the sign of the <f type="i">Leg</f>
and <f type="i">Star</f>, over against the <f type="i">Royal Ex&shy;
change</f>, in <f type="i">Cornhil</f>, 1674.
</section>
 </page>


<page sig="[A1r]">
<section type="To the Reader">
<heading>
To the Reader.
</heading>

<f type="i">I hope, after twelve years experience in the busi&shy;
ness of Schooling, I may be thought sufficiently
sensible of those distracting troubles, and anxieties;
that perpetually attend the Calling. The removal
of some of these is the principal end of the present
undertaking.

The contradictions that are every day propos'd
to little Children, how can they choose but puzl and
torment them, when the Masters themselves (that
pursue the common method) are so miserably con&shy;
founded, and utterly unable to reconcile their way
of spelling with an English pronunciation?

The Rule that I lay down is brief and plain
and easie:</f> viz. <f type="i">All words must so be spell'd, as
they are afterwards to be pronounc'd. But this
they dare not venture on, for fear (forsooth) of
straying from the common road, or slighting of
a rule that was made and intended only for the
Latin tongue. See, I have broke the ice: and
that in such a natural, familiar, and pleasant me&shy;
 </page>


<page sig="[A1v]">
that, the Child shall have waded thorow three
parts (at least) of all the words that are used in
English Authors, before he meets with any conside&shy;
rable irregularity.

I could enlarge, but I reserve it for another place.
The trial of a few hours will fully satisfie the man
that doubts, and more than answer any reasonable
expectation.

C. Coles
</section>
 </page>


<page no="1">
<heading>
The Alphabet.
</heading>

<editoraddition>27-letter alphabet (including long-s) in roman, italic, and black-letter fonts is not included here.</editoraddition>
</page>

<page no="98">

</page>
<page no="99">
<section type="Useful Observations on Orthography">
AN
<f type="i">APPENDIX</f>
OF Useful Observations
On O<emend err="">R</emend>THOGRAPHY.

But before I proceed, I must give you a brief
account of what I have done already.

<subsection type="Of the Alphabet">
<f type="i">Of the Alphabet.</f>

IN the Letters are commonly considered three
things. <f type="i">viz</f>: The name, the figure, and the power:
This power should be included in the name; and
the difference both of figure and power together, should
produce a different name. This name and power, so
often thwarting one another, has given occasion to sev&shy;
eral endeavours of correction; and as I believe, some
gradual correction to be feasible, so I believe that a sud&shy;
den and universal alteration is altogether impossible.
Some are so fondly wedded to their toothless antiquity,
</page>

<page no="100">
they would not for a world sit out of their Grandam's
lap, and deserve not to be envy'd their felicity: If they
are not sensible of the absurdity, their Eyes, Ears and
Brains are not all worth three-pence, as <f type="i">Ben. Johnson</f>
observ'd long ago (in his English Grammar).

I in the other power (meaning a consonant) is meerly
another letter, and would ask to enjoy another cha&shy;
racter.

He's pleasured, It has obtain'd; and by the addition 
of <f type="i">jod</f> and <f type="i">van</f>, or (as some call 'em) <f type="i">jea</f> and <f type="i">vee</f>, the
number is encreas'd to 26.

But he that intends a different type for every diffe&shy;
rent force of every particular letter, will handsomly aug&shy;
ment his Alphabet, and miserably confound the Com&shy;
positor and his Founts. He must have four <f type="i">a's</f> at least,
as Fall, Father, Fame, Pharoah. He must, have six
or seven <f type="i">e's</f>; as Equal, Peter, Were, Even, Ever, Yes,
Her: and as many <f type="i">i's</f>; as Will, Wile, Intrigue, Me&shy;
dicine, Birth, Shire, Irk, &c. Nay, not the Vowels on&shy;
ly but the Consonants also (whose sound is sometime va&shy;
riant, sometime single, sometime double, and sometime 
none at all,) will require three or four characters apiece;
as Abel, Habit, Subtle: and sometimes more, as Scept&shy;
ick, Civil, Schism, Second, Facile; as Gin, Begin, 
Legend, Legacy, Gnaw, Gnat, &c. And because of
the several hands that are writ and printed, the great and
small forms, &c. he'll need the utmost assistance of
<f type="i">Cadmus, Palamedes, Simonides, Mercury; Proteus</f>, and 
<f type="i">Apollo</f> himself. Some general distinctions have been
propos'd by Mr. <f type="i">Butler</f>, Doctor <f type="i">Wallis</f>, and others:
but the wise, consciencious and ingenious have been so
few all along, that they have not been able to bear it up
against the stream of the ignorant, lazy, boisterous and
self-conceited populace. <f type="i"><term lang="la">Frangas enim citius qu&agrave;m cor&shy;
tigas qu&aelig; in pravum induruerunt.</term></f> Mr. <f type="i">Butler's</f> reforma&shy;
</page>


<page no="101">
tion was grounded on the old original Teutonick, and
was something too violent. For (as I sad before) what&shy;
soever is done in this particular, must be (and will be)
leisurely and by degrees: the greatest impediment
hath been from the Printers: whereof some were igno&shy;
rant, some were inable, and othersome were obstinate:
but now their knowledge, power, and compliance will
prove the greatest furtherance.

They are sufficiently sollicited: no new types are re&shy;
quired, and I know nothing but malice, that can be ob&shy;
jected. 'Tis an easie matter to let the broad &acirc;, &icirc;, and &ocirc; be
circumflected; to make the strong s long, and the soft one
short. 'Tis easie to distinguish the soft <f type="i">ch</f> and <f type="i">th</f> from 
those that are strong and hard, by a different character
(suppose the full and round letter strong, and the black
<f type="i">Italian</f> letter soft, or <f type="i">vice vers&agrave;</f>: yet this is all. There
needs no different characters for <f type="i">c</f> and <f type="i">g</f> save when they
are strong before <f type="i">e</f> and <f type="i">i</f>, and that's but in very few
words; as <f type="i">C</f>is, <f type="i">C</f>edron, <f type="i">Ac</f>eldama, <f type="i">Sc</f>eleton, <f type="i">Sc</f>eptick;
An<f type="i">g</f>er, dag<f type="i">g</f>er, En<f type="i">g</f>edi, fin<f type="i">g</f>er, lin<f type="i">g</f>er, <f type="i">g</f>eese, <f type="i">g</f>eld, <f type="i">g</f>et, <f type="i">G</f>en&shy;
nesaret, <f type="i">G</f>er<f type="i">gesene, <f type="i">G</f>ethsemane, <f type="i">g</f>ewgaws, hetero<f type="i">g</f>ene&shy;
ous, homo<f type="i">g</f>eneous, stag<f type="i">g</f>er, swag<f type="i">g</f>er, tar<f type="i">g</f>et, to<f type="i">g</f>ether;
<f type="i">G</f>ibeon, <f type="i">g</f>ibberish, <f type="i">G</f>ibbons, <f type="i">g</f>iddy, <f type="i">g</f>ift, <f type="i">g</f>i<f type="i">g, <f type="i">G</f>ilbert,
<f type="i">G</f>ilboa, <f type="i">g</f>ild, <f type="i">G</f>ilgal, <f type="i">g</f>ills, <f type="i">g</f>imlet, be<f type="i">g</f>in, bi<f type="i">gg</f>in, pi<f type="i">gg</f>in,
no<f type="i">gg</f>in, <f type="i">G</f>inny, <f type="i">g</f>ittern, <f type="i">g</f>ive, and (it may be) one or two
more. 

Touching the instilling of these first elementary prin&shy;
ciples into children, take one Observation from the
great School-master <f type="i">Quintilian<f>.

<f type="i"><term lang="la">Non excludo autem id quod est notum, irritanda ad dis&shy;
cendum Infanti&aelig; grati&acirc;, Eburneas etiam literarum for&shy;
mus in lusum offerre, vel siquid aliud quo magis illa &aelig;tas
gaudeat, inveniri potest, quod tractare, intueri, nominare
jucundum sit. C&ugrave;m ver&ograve; jam ductus sequi c&oelig;perit, non mu&shy;
tile erat. eas tabell&aelig; qu&agrave;m optim&egrav</f> e; insculpi, ut per illos ve&shy;
lut su'cos ducatur stylus.</term></f> l.1.c.1.
</page>

<page no="102">
Take notice first, how soon he begins to inform them,
and that's as soon as ever they begin to imitate your
speech (for I see no reason why his Infantia may not be)
taken properly): and then the method, by giving
them graven images of ivory letters to play withal, or
elss in sugar, or whatsoever else you see they take de&shy;
light in  And so soon as his hand (saies he) is capable of
imitation, let him draw something like a pen through
the furrows of a letter neatly cut upon a little board.
</subsection>
</page>

<page no="103">
<subsection type="The Tables">
<heading>
Of the TABLES.
</heading>

CHildren are not to be troubled with Rules and
Exceptions; with Definitions, and Distincti&shy;
ons.

Their Judgment is little or none at all, but they are
actively capable of imitation, to the wonder of our
Natural Historian. Therefore I fall immediately upon
practice.

The first practical Table is plain, even to superfluity;
without confounding their weakness with notions of 
Guttural, Palatine, and Labial sounds, and without
propounding any feigned uncouth <f type="i">g</f>ibberish; where&shy;
as we have plain examples enough of real English
words. But because men usually espouse that pro&shy;
nunciation as properest which they have been accu&shy;
stom'd to, therefore they will be quarrelling at some
particulars.

Let them know, that in these things I have been jea&shy;
lous of, and oftentimes divorc'd my self, and have fol&shy;
low'd that pronunciation which I have for many years
observ'd to be most in use among the generality of Schol&shy;
ars: I have had opportunity of making observations.

I was born and bred [for a dozen years] in the very
heart of <f type="i">England</f>, I spent almost as many in her very
eye, and after that as many more in [or about] the
very head of all the Kingdom.
</page>

<page no="104">

Moreover, I have perus'd the most approved of our
English Poets, whose general consent in timing is the
best authority the case is capable of.

<f type="i">Bold sons of<f> Adam, <f type="i">when in fire ye crawl
Thus high to be
Perch'd on the tree,
Remember but the fall, Cleevl.</f> 97

<f type="i">And then a Serpentine do'st crawl
Now a straight line, now rookt, now all</f>
Lovelace, Luc. 15.
<f type="i">The Kings imparti'al anger light's on all
From fly-blown Acc'ron to the thundring Baal.</f>
Cowl. Dav. 60.

This proves that Baal in English is but one syllable,
and has the sound of ball and bawl.

A large collection of these I have at hand, which
might be (if occasion were) produc'd.

The second Table is as plain as the first, without per&shy;
plexing them (again) with Simple and Compound,
primitive or derivative, and such kind of conjuring stuff.
To what purpose are children bid to put a difference be&shy;
tween their English and the Greek or Hebrew
words? What ear-mark shall they know them by?
Or, do we Schoolmen our selves indeed know which
are which? I doubt when we have once substracted
the words that are of the <f type="i">Brittish, French, Latin,
Greek, Hebrew</f>, and <f type="i">Persian</f> derivation (wherein
the Etymologists are exceeding defective) I doubt we
should have but a poor pittance left us of English or
Saxon words. I follow the common way as far as I am
able; yet not because it is the common way, but be&shy;
cause it agrees so far with my principle, and does not
contradict the proper end of spelling, which clearly de&shy;
</page>

<page no="105"> 
monstrates my aversion to innovation, except where
absolute necessity requires it.

'Tis in the last two Tables that I contradict that com&shy;
mon way of Spelling which contradicts it self: In this
place therefore I condem the antick, and justifie my mo&shy;
dern Method.

Spell, in old English signifies a word, and to spell, is to
word it; or handle words in general. But by use it has
obtain'd a stricter meaning, <f type="i">viz</f>. the gradual composing
of words and such a resolving them again into syllables
and letters.

This is useful so far (and no farther than) as it is sub&shy;
servient to true reading, writing and speaking, and con&shy;
sequently to our understanding of one anothers minds
for mutual converse. So far as it doth not answer this
end, so far it is defective, or erronius. But the common
way of spelling, doth not only answer this end of 
assisting the true pronunciation in speaking and reading, 
but is quite contradictory and very prejudicial to it, <f type="i">e.g.</f>
Their grand and fundamental Rule is this, whatsoever 
letters may begin a word, must also begin a syllable.

First therefore I desire to know why they themselves
write Gyp-sy, Jas-per, Scep-tick, &c. when they had
told us that <f type="i">ps</f>, <f type="i">sp</f> and <f type="i">pt</f> would begin words?

Secondly, there are almost two thousand English
words, which, if they were so spel'd would quite lose
their English pronunciation: as may be seen at large, in
the 3d. and 4th. tables. The Foundation being shaken
the superstructure also totters.

A single consonant (say they) between two vowels
must needs be joyned to the following vowel. Shew me
the ground of this necessity: I say there are no such Eng&shy;
lish words as a-ni-mate, e-ve-ry, de-li-ver, &c. and
it needs no other proof than the having on a pair of Eng&shy;
lish (not <f type="i">Arcadian</f>) ears. Again, when the sound (say
</page>

<page no="106">
they) rests hard upon a consonant, then it must be dou&shy;
bled. Therefore we are bound to write habbit, stud&shy;
dy, and to commit above a thousand more such barba&shy;
rous absurdities: and therefore they themselves write
shaddow, widdow, tallent, &c.

I'll instance in one more, <f type="i">ti</f> before a vowel is sounded
like <f type="i">si</f>.

This Rule is absolutely false. For there is not one
word in all the English world (let their extraction be
what it will) where <f type="i">ti</f> sounds <f type="i">si</f> (except <f type="i">totius</f> be an Eng&shy;
lish word.) I know how syllables are drawn out in
singing &c. but I speak of the proper pronunciation
of common English prose.

One word more of the first original of these mis&shy;
takes.

Dr. <f type="i">Wallis</f> observes (in the pr&aelig;face to his English
Grammar) how all the English <f type="i">Grammarians</f> have con&shy;
founded our language by their violent forcing it to the
Latin method.

<f type="i"><term lang="la">Omnes enim ad Latin&aelig; lingu&aelig; normam hanc nostrum
Anglicanam nimium exigentes multa mutilia pr&aelig;cepta de
Nominum casibus -- alijeque similibus tradiderunt, que
lingu&aelig; nostr&aelig; sunt prorsus aliena; adeoque confusionem po&shy;
tius &amp; obscuritatem pariunt;, qu&agrave;m explicationi inser&shy;
viunt.</term></f>

Because they had met with such and such Rules for the
dividing of words in Latin therefore the English must of
necessity be just so divided! Those Latin Rules were suit&shy;
ed to the Latin pronunciation. And if Latin had been
naturally pronounc'd as we pronounce it now, those
Rules had been as improper for that language, as they
are for ours. 'Tis folly for any language to be guided
(in this particular) by another on which it hath no de&shy;
pendence and the Dr. hath prov'd that ours was in being
before the Latin. But considering the end of spelling
</page>

<page no="107">
in all languages (which is the teaching to read or to
speak) the true Rule of spelling (in all languages whatso&shy;
ever,) is this;

Words are so to be spelt, as they are afterwards to
be pronounc'd. But for men to teach folk to spell a
word one way, and then to pronounce it another; what
pitiful senseless contradiction is this! Yet nothing is
more frequent among us. N, a, na; t, i, si; nasi, o, n, 
on: put it together, it must be pronounced either na-si-
on (which word is no where to be found) or na-shun, and
so he must contradict himself. We are taught to spell
<f type="i">Ab-ra-ham</f>, and afterward to pronounce it <f type="i">A-bra-ham</f>;
to spell <f type="i">Ba-al</f>, and pronounce it <f type="i">Bawl</f>; to spell bo-dy,
and pronounce it bod-dy, or something that is worse: I
have seen this very thing confound and puzzle the poor
children most abominably.

But how should it otherwise chuse, when it will con&shy;
found the best of those Teachers to reconcile them.
They themselves are so far sensibly convinc'd of this,
that on this very ground they have given new names to 
some letters, and added other new ones to the number
(for a new name, force, and figure do make an absolute
new letter).

<f type="i">Ai</f> and <f type="i">au</f> (say they) more clearly direct the Lear&shy;
ner to the true sound of the words, than <f type="i">a-i</f> and <f type="i">a-u</f> di&shy;
vided, &c.

And in another place, in spelling this word Physici&shy;
an, say not p, h, y, phy; for p, h, divided lead not
at all to the true sound of the syllable, &c.

And had this principle been thorowly pursued, most
of my labour had been spared. For if the letters are
so to be named, as may lead to the after-pronuncia&shy;
tion of the syllable; why not the syllables also so di&shy;
vided, as may lead to the after-pronunciation of the
word?
</page>

<page no="108">
But those men are exceedingly to blame, whose lazy,
cowardise (on this account) hath prompted them to
throw off spelling altogether. I hope my method hath
so far remov'd the difficulties, that we shall hencefor&shy;
ward all agree; so well prevented the contradictions,
that we may both teach and learn with more delight,
more confidence and profit.
</subsection>
</page>

<page no="109">
<subsection type="Orthography">
<heading>
Of <f type="i">Orthography</f>.
</heading>

<f type="i"><term lang="la">INgredienti mihi rationem, scribendi, occurrit statim,
ita quosdam censuisse, esse scribendum ut loquimur &amp;
audimus. Vel Longus. Grammatici unus finis est, recte
loqui, Neque necesse habes scribere. Accidit enim scriptu&shy;
ra voci, neque aliter scribere debemus, qu&agrave;m loquamur.
Jul. C&aelig;s. Scaliger.

Prosodia autem &amp; Orthographia partes non sunt, sed
ut sanguis &amp; spiritus per corpus universum fuse.</f></term> Ramus.

But the Grave and truly Classick Author is <f type="i">Quintili&shy;
an</f>, that had been a School-master twenty years, before
he wrote his Institutions. <f type="i"><term lang="la">Per viginti annos erudiendis
Juvenibus studia impenderam. Proam Merit&ograve; igitur a
Poet&acirc; Coco Fabius vocatur Vog&aelig; Juventa summus Mode&shy;
rator. D. Pareus.</term></f>

The Panegyrick in <f type="i">Martial</f> begins thus.

<term lang="la">Quintiliane <f type="i">vag&aelig; Moderator summe Juventa,
Gloria Roman&aelig; Quintiliane tog&aelig;.</term></f> I.11.Ep.90.

 The greater this mans authority is, the greater is the fault
 of perverting his meaning. Yet some body (sure Mr.
 Cocker doth not, but) grosly belies him, in saying he
 would have us write, exactly as we speak.
 
 His own words are these, in the seventeenth chapter
 of his first book: <f type="i"><term lang="la">Ego (nisi quod consuetudo obtinuerit)
 sic scribendum quicqui judico, quomodo sonat.</term> </f> If the pa&shy;
 renthesis indeed were out, it would be something to the 
 </page>
 
 <page no="110">
 purpose. But he speaks again without a parenthesis:
 <f type="i"><term lang="la">Ver&ugrave;m Orthographia quoque consuetudini servit ideoque
 s&aelig;pe mutata est. ibid.</term></f>
 
 I take not out of the Writing Masters hands, what
 they think proper to themselves; I complain they are
 <emend err="are"></emend> so defective, and have appropriated to themselves
 no more; for what's the making of a letter to their great
 profession of Pen-man-ship? 'Tis true that Orthogra&shy;
 phy (true and fair writing) can no more be without let&shy;
 ters, than a house without beams and bricks, &c. but
 those directions that go no further, will as soon accom&shy;
 plish their end, as the making of bricks, and squaring of
 Timber will perfect a buildinbg, of Ornament and service,
 As for their Ornaments and curiosities, they are often&shy;
 times extravagant. And under pretense of flourishing a 
 letter, they make it frequently another, or rather none
 at all. One who pretended unto skill in these affairs
 was pleas'd to commend and shew me one of <f type="i">Gethings</f> 
 Copy-books. I took the book, and doubled down the 
 Copy as far as the great initial, and pray'd him to tell
 me the name of the letter.
 
 The Gentleman was so uncivil as to nick-name it. I
 doubled down another, he (conscious of his former er&shy;
 rour) cry'd <f type="i">Ignoramus</f>. I do by no means condemn (nay I
 commend and admire) their ingenuity, their fancy and 
 dexterity. But these things ought to keep their pro&shy;
 per places; not to perplex and disturb the Orthogra&shy;
 phy, not so to confound and abuse the very Masters themselves to
 determine which is which. Of those things that might
 be spared we have enough and to spare: but little enough
 of that which is absolutely necessary. Mr. <f type="i">Hodder</f> (I
 think) hath ventur'd farthest of any, in this Rule for joyn&shy;
 ing, where one letter ends the other must begin.
 
 And why might we not as well have been directed,
 </page>
 
 <page no="111">
 when to use the great letters, and when the small ones?
 Why might we not have been instructed, how to divide
 our words when we have occasion (as we have in every
 other time almost?) And why not one word about the
 stops and pointing what we write? Tell me not these
 things belong to the Grammar; doth not all you do, be&shy;
 long to Grammar? I am sure the understanding of these
 things belongs to all that intend to fit themselves for
 commerce and conversation in the world, for answering
 the end of their creation, and doing service unto God
 in their Generation.
 
 <heading>
 The Use of Capital or Great Letters.
 </heading>
 
 The Great Letters are called Capitals, either First, be&shy;
 cause the little ones are derived from them as their head;
 or, Secondly, because of their large bulk and appear&shy;
 ance with a head above the rest: or lastly, by reason of
 their use in signifying some head, that is, some first,
 Principal, Emphatical, Remarkable, or Eminent
 thing.
 
 These things of note or eminency are reckon'd up by
 many, and by Mr. <f type="i">Daines</f> above the rest: but all that
 I ever saw are exceeding imperfect. I will not warrant
 absolute perfection, but I promise to mend the matter 
 by some necessary and useful additions.
 
 Now these Capital Letters do either compose whole
 words and clauses, or else they serve for initials only.
 Of the first sort are the titles of Books, and their divi&shy;
 sions: as THE HOLIE BIBLE, &c. THE FIRST
 BOOK OF MOSES CALLED GENESIS,
 CHAP. I. &c.
 
 And whatsoever is thus wholly exprest by Capitals,
 is alwaies more then ordinarily remarkable; as some
 signal name, Title, Inscription, or the like, <f type="i">e.g.</f> I Am
 </page>
 
 <page no="112">
 <f type="i">THAT I AM</f>, Exod. 3. 14. (take notice that the
 word I is alway so writ, <f type="i">My name JEHOVAH</f>, 
 Exod. 6.3.
 
 And grave upon it like the ingravings of a Signet,
 <f type="i">HOLINESS TO THE LORD</f>, Exod. 28. 36. & 39.
 20. That thou mayest fear this glorious and fearfull
 name, <f type="i">THE LORD THY GOD</f>, Deut. 28. 58. And
 this is his name whereby he shall be called, <f type="i">THE LORD
 OUR RIGHTEOUSNESS</f>. Jer. 23. 6. And this is
 the writing that was written, <f type="i">MENE MENE
 TEKEL UPHARSIN</f>, Dan. 5.25. Behold the man,
 whose name is <f type="i">THE BRANCH</f>, Zech. 6. 12. <f type="i">THIS
 IS JESUS THE KING OF THE JEWS</f>, Mat.
 27. 37. <f type="i">JESUS OF NAZARETH THE KING
 OF THE JEWS</f>, John 19. 19. <f type="i">TO THE VN&shy;
 KNOWN GOD</f>, Act. 17. 20. And on her forehead was
 a name written, <f type="i">MYSTERY, BABYLON THE
 GREAT, THE MOTHER OF HARLOTS AND 
 ABOMINATIONS OF THE EARTH</f>, Rev. 17.
 5. And he hath on his vesture and on his thigh a name
 written, <f type="i">KING OF KINGS AND LORD OF
 LORDS</f>, Rev. 19. 16.
 
 To these many more might be added out of other
 Books; but these I judged of greatest consequence to
 children. Only take notice that there is also a very
 great difference between these Capitals themselves;
 and such words (among them) as are more notable and
 eminent, have (proportionally to their note and emi&shy;
 nence) either the first or all the letters in a larger form
 than the rest. Hence it is, that in every chapter (almost)
 of the Bible, the first letter is a larger, and the second
 (whether it be in the same word or no) a smaller Capi&shy;
 tal. As in the first Epistle to Timothy PAUL an Apo&shy;
 stle I exhort therefore --- This is a true saying, Rebuke
 not an Elder -- LEt as many servants -- This leads us to
 </page>
 
 <page no="113">
 to the other use of the Capitals, when they serve for initi&shy;
 als only. And as those directions did principally con&shy;
 cern the Reader, so these that follow do chiefly require
 the writers observation.
 
 1. All those words that are at any time wholly com&shy;
 pos'd of Capitals, must alwaies have the first letter a 
 Capital one.
 
 2. All names of Persons, Dignities, Relations, Offices,
 Arts, Daies, Months, Winds and Places; are to begin
 with a Capital or great letter. This will be much il&shy;
 lustrated by an induction of some particulars.

God the Father, Son and Holy Ghost. Jesus Christ, 
Jesuite, Christian. Heathen God and Goddesses. Sa&shy;
turn, Jupiter, Apollo, Mars, Mercury, Bachus, Ba&shy;
al; Juno, Minerva, Venus, Ashteroth, &c. Angel,
Devil, Michael, Raphael, Belzebub, Legion, &c.
Adam, Adamite, Charles Stuart, Eve, Catharine,
&c. His Majesty, Highness, Grace; Your Honour,
Worship; Sir, Madame, Monarch, Emperour, Em&shy;
peress, King, Queen, Parliament, Pope, Patriarch,
Cardinal, Bishop, Dean, Prehend, Doctor, &c.
Lord, Lady, Prince, Duke, Dutchess, Marquess,
Earl, Countess, Viscount, Baron, Knight, Esquire,
Gentleman, Master, Mistress, &c. Father, Mother,
Uncle, Aunt, Brother, &c. Ambassador, Commis&shy;
sioner, Legate, Nuncio, Agent, Plenipotentiary, 
Chancellor, Treasurer, Governour, Warden, Presi&shy;
dent, &c. Magistrate, Minister, The Court, Judges,
Justices, &c. Officer, Commander, General, Ad&shy;
miral, Colonel, Captain, Lieutenant, &c. Gram&shy;
mar, Logick, Rhetorick, Musick, Arithmetick, Ge&shy;
ometry, Astronomy; Grammarian, Architect, Mer&shy;
cer, &c. Sunday, Monday; January, February,
Shrovetide, Lent, Easter, &c. East, West, &c.
Europe, France, England, Thames, London, Cheap&shy;
</page>

<page no="106">
 side, White-hall, Corpus Christi Colledge, &c.
 
 3. Every sentence must begin with a Capital letter.
 Thus the Rule is generally propos'd, without any
 more adoe: but I have something considerable to say
 to it. The meaning is, that every Treatise, Book,
 Chapter, Section and Paragraph must begin with a
 great letter. That's plain enough. When (by the
 Rules of pointing) you are come to a full stop, or pe&shy;
 riod; signifi'd by one title, thus (.) then the sentence
 is out: and the next that follows, must begin again
 with a great letter. This is also plain enough. But
 you must know that sometimes a sentence is reckoned
 to begin, and so consequently a great letter is to be
 made, when there was no full stop afore it. <f type="i">E.g.</f>
 
 1. When the words of another are quoted, they al&shy;
 waies begin with a great letter. Gen. 1. 3.
 <f type="i">And God said, Let there be Light.</f>
 
And when propounded to another to say after you,
Judg. 12.6. <f type="i">Say now Shibboleth</f>. See the gene&shy;
ral Confessions and Creed, in the Liturgie.

2. In epistles there is seldom a full stop after the
Compellation, yet the next letter is reckon'd
to begin the treatise, and must be a great one.
Of the same nature is the Subscription at the
bottom, because it is written apart from the
rest.

3. A new particular oftentimes begins in the midst
of a sentence, and then it must of necessity be&shy;
gin the line with a great letter, as
In the beginning of

1. Sentences
2. All proper names
 
4. For the same reason, because every verse must begin
</page>

<page no="107">
a new line, therefore it must hav a great letter,
though the sense preceding were not perfect.
<f type="i">Gen.</f> 1.17.18. And God set them in the firmament
of the Heaven, to give light upon the earth:
And to Rule over the day and over the night, </f>&c.
 
Lastly. Whatsoever words the Author laies any
kind of stress of force upon, these he either
writes in a different character, or else prefixes
a Capital before them, or both. Hence those
that think they write nothing but strength of
wit and thunderbolts, will scarce vouchsafe
 you two words together without a Capital.
 They are indeed so much in fashion, that I reck&shy;
 on this a good Rule to go by, <f type="i">viz.</f>
 
 Whensoever you are in doubt, whether you had
 best write a little letter or a great one, be sure
 you write a great one. For this is the safest
 hand to erre on.
 
 <heading>
 <f type="i">The dividing of words.</f>
 </heading>
 
 A syllable is not to be divided. The Rule is sound
 and good. The question will be, what a syllable is. A
 syllable (say some) is that number of letters as are spelt
 together at once. And the result from thence is this:
 You must not part asunder, what you must put toge&shy;
 ther.
 
 Others are more critical, and say, that a syllable is a
 </page>
 
 <page no="108">
 taking letters together, and uttering them with one
 breath. So that Three blue beans in a blue bladder, rattle
 bladder rattle, is not the third part of a syllable, except 
 you are short winded. For 'tis all but on breath, though
 often intercepted and struck into several sounds. One
 comes a little closer to the bus'ness (if he doth but under&shy;
 stand himself,) when he saies, for spelling right, the
 syllables you'l find by parting them in sound within your
 mind. But his examples and the rest of his method
 strikes into the common road, that leads both him and
 all of 'em into the common errour.
 
 'Tis not the combination of consonants, but 'tis the
 ear that must distinguish syllables by the stop that is be&shy;
 tween them. In Scripture we stop not at Scri (as 'tis
 usually divided) but at Scrip: in Question we stop not
 at Que, but at Ques, &c. And so should the sound de&shy;
 termine every syllable or division. Otherwise the pro&shy;
 nunciation of one part must be suspended, till you know
 the other. When <f type="i">Scaliger</f> saies we must write as we
 speak, understand him thus; or else he'll make mad
 work of it: As the old Grammarian <f type="i">V. Longus</f> hath ob&shy;
 serv'd: <f type="i"><term lang="la">C&ugrave;m dicimus Hic est ille, unum c scribimus &
 duo audimus. Ergo scribendum est per duo c, Hoc c erat
 alam Parens? aut confitendum, quadam aliter scribi, a&shy;
 liter enuntiari.</term></f>
 </subsection>
 </page>

<page no="109">
<subsection type="Abbreviations">
<heading>
Abbreviations.
</heading>

THese have been touch'd upon by several Authors,
and some Writing-Masters, but exceeding slightly,
considering their large extent and use.

Some of them are common with us and other Na&shy;
tions.

1. Arithmetical figures to express both whole num&shy;
bers and fractions. 1. 2. 3. 4. 1/2 &#8532; 3/4, &c.

2. Geometrical: as, === parallel, &delta; triangle, &#2011; &c.
 
 3. Astronomical: as &#2648; Aries, &#2649; Taurus, &c. &#2644; Sa&shy;
 turn, &#2643; Jupiter, &c. &#260A; Dragons head &#260B; Dragons
 tail, &#260C;  Conjunction, &#260D; Opposition, &c.
 
 4. Musical: as &#1D15D; Sim'brief, &#1D15E; Minum,  &#1D15F; Crotch&shy;
 et, &c. 
 
 5. Medicinal: as, &#215E; (Recipe) take. &#8468; (libra) a
 pound, &#00DF; (semissis) half a pound, &#2125; an ounce, &#0292; a dram,
 &#2108; a scruple, gr. a grain, m. (<term lang="la">manipulus</term>) a handfull, p. a
 pugil or half a handfull,  <f type="i">ana</f>, of each a like,  <f type="i">q. s., (<term lang="la">quan&shy;
 tum satis</term>)</f> a sufficient quantity, <f type="i">q. l. (<term lang="la">quantum libet</term>)</f> as
 much as you please, <f type="i">&c.</f> most of these are Latin, So
  
 2. There are many more abbreviations which we bor&shy;
 row from the Latin, and use upon all occasions, <f type="i"><term lang="la">vi&shy;
 delicet</term></f>) that is to say, <f type="i">e.g.</f> (<f type="i"><term lang="la">exempli gratia</term></f> as for exam&shy;
 (ple <f type="i">l. s. d. qu.</f> (<f type="i"><term lang="la">libri, solidi, denarii, quadrantes</term></f>)
 pounds, shillings, pence, farthings, <f type="i">l. c. v.</f> (<f type="i"><term lang="la">liber, caput,</term>
 versus</f>) book, chapter, verse, <f type="i">p.</f> (<f type="i"><term lang="la">pagina</term></f>) page. &#00A7; (<f type="i"><term lang="la">sectio</term></f>)
 section, <f type="i">v.</f> (<f type="i">vide)</f> see. <f type="i">n.l.</f> (<f type="i"><term lang="la">non liquit</term></f>) it doth not ap&shy;
 </page>
 
 <page no="110">
pear, <f type="i">i.e.</f> (<f type="i"><term lang="la">id est</term></f>) that is, <f type="i">sc. (<term lang="la">scilicet</term></f>) to wit, <f type="i">s.a.</f> (<f type="i"><term lang="la">sine
authoritate</term></f>) without authority, <f type="i">q.d.</f> (<f type="i"><term lang="la">quasi dicat</term></f>) as if
he should say, <f type="i">N.B. (<term lang="la">nota bene</term>)</f> take special notice of
this, M.S. Manuscript, <f type="i">M. A. <f type="i">(<term lang="la">Magister Artium</term>)</f>
Master of arts, <f type="i">J.D.</f> or <f type="i">L.D. (<term lang="la">Juris aut Legis Doctor</term></f>)
Doctor of Law, <f type="i">B.D. (<term lang="la">Baccalaurium Divinitatis</term></f>) Bat&shy;
chelor of Divinity, <f type="i"></f>D. D.</f> or <f type="i">S. S. Th. D.</f> (<f type="i"><term lang="la">Sacrosan&shy;
ct&aelig; Theologi&aelior</term></f>) Doctor of Divinity, <f type="i">Ob.</f> (Ob&shy;
jection<f type="i"></f>,) Sol.</f> Solution. MDLXXIII. One thousand six
hundred seventy three.

So from the Grammarians, <f type="i">m.</f> masculine, <f type="i">f.</f> feminine,
<f type="i">a.</f> active, <f type="i">p.</f> passive, <f type="i">n.</f> neuter, <f type="i">&c.</f> and so forth.

The other contractions that are more properly ours,
are these that follow.

1. The old farrago of common words more complete,
Ag<sup>t</sup>. against, Adm<sup>rs</sup> Administrators, Bp. Bishop, Com<sup>rs</sup>,
Commissioners, d<sup>d</sup>, deliver, Dr. Doctor, Esq; Esquire,
H<sup>d</sup>. Honoured, H<sup>ble</sup> Honourable, Ill<sup>us</sup>, Illustrious, Kt.
Knight, L<sup>d</sup>, Lord, L<sup>p</sup>. Lordship, l<sup>r</sup>, letter, M<sup>d</sup>, Memo&shy;
randum, Mts. Majesty, mme Madam, Mr. Master, Mrs.
Mistress, N. such a one or such a one, Obt. Obedient,
pd. paid, qd quoth, qr. quarter, qt. quantity, recd, re&shy;
ceived, sd. said, Servt. Servant, Sr. Sir, St. Saint, ye, the
y<sup>n</sup> then, y<sup>t</sup> that, Trear. Treasurer, w<sup>t</sup>, what, w<sup>n</sup>. when,
w<sup>ch</sup>, which, w<sup>th</sup>. with, W<sup>p</sup>. Worship, W<sup>ll</sup>. Worship&shy;
full, o<sup>r</sup>. our, yo<sup>r</sup>. your, (The y that stands forth is a
corruption of the old Saxon character of th: and the
friends may take notice that you and thou are all one)
1st. first, 2dly. secondly, 3d. third, 4th. fourth, &c. 7ber.
September, 8ber. October, 9ber. November, 10ber.
December, Jan. January, Feb. February, <f type="i">&c.</f>) <f type="i">Com.</f> or
<f type="i">Con</f>, &#101A0; per,  pr. pre</expan>, &#0239;. pro, mt. ment, <f type="i">Q.</f> Question,
<f type="i">A.</f> Answer, <f type="i">D.</f> Doctrine, <f type="i">R. </f> Reason, <f type="i">V.</f> Use, <f type="i">&c.</f>
Two words are often<emend err="ten"></emend>times contracted into one. 'Tis
'twas, 'twill, for, it is, it was, it will, don't for do not,
</page>

<page no="111">
cannot, Th'other, th'annunciation, for the other, <f type="i">&c.</f>
Topsy turvy, for Th' upside, th'other way, Let's for
Let us. The pot's never from's nose, for The pot is ne&shy;
ver from his nose, <f type="i">Democr. Jun.</f> I'll, I will, I'm, I am,
Thou'lt, Thou wilt, He'ld, He would, &c.

<heading>
2. <f type="i">Proper Names.</f>
</heading>

1. Of Places; as Bucks, Buckinghamshire, Exon,
Excester, Oxon, Oxford, C.C.C. Corpus Christi Col&shy;
ledge, &c.

2. Of Book; as Gen. Genesis, Eccles. Ecclesiastes, Ec&shy;
clus Ecclesiasticus, &c.

3. Of men; as C. R. Charles Rex, Alex. Alexander,
Will. William, &c.

In Comedians and other familiar and contemptuous
discourses we frequently meet with their Nick-nams.
And because I never knew this business touch'd by any
(though it be as needful as any thing else to the learning
of the language) therefore I have added this following
collection.

<heading>
Pointing.
</heading>

The business of pointing is punctual enough in others.
I only design'd a supply of such material points, as were
not to be had else-where. Therefore I refer you to Mr.
<f type="i">Lewis</f>, and put a period to this discourse, with this one
observation from <f type="i">Quintilian</f>: <f type="i"><term lang="la">Scribendum ergo qu&agrave;m
optime scribamus; celeritatem dabit consuetudo. Summa
h&aelig;c est rei, Cit&ograve; scribendo non fit ut bene scribatur: bene
scribendo fit ut cit&ograve;</term></f> Id. Ibid.
</subsection>

<closing>
<f type="i">FINIS.</f>
</section>
</page>
</leme>
